cluding those in uniform, respond to the violence of racism? And how was their resistance, including their claims to manhood and nation, understood by law enforcement, politicians, and the press?Building on extensive archival research, the book examines how African and Mexican American men have been constructed as ‘racial problems’, investigating, in particular, their relationship with law enforcement and ideas about black and Mexican criminality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican AmericanszUnited StatesxSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aMexican AmericanszUnited StatesxSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aRacismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aUnited StatesxRace relationsy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aAfrican Americans.  aImmigration.  aMasculinity.  aMexican Americans.  aNation.  aPolice brutality.  aRacism.  aResistance.  aRiots.  aSegregation.1 aAragon, Margarita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSolomos, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVirdee, Satnam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWinter, Aaron, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2021 eBook-Packagez978311128198840uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152612168440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526121684423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526121684/original  a978-3-11-128198-8  Manchester University Press 2021 eBook-Packageb2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles